# 🧠 1. Core idea

`BrowserView` lives in **Electron’s main process**, not the renderer.

So you build:

```text
Main Process
  → BrowserWindow (your app shell)
  → BrowserView (real browser tab)
```

---

# ⚙️ 2. Minimal working example

## 📦 Install Electron

```bash
npm init -y
npm install electron
```

---

## 📁 `main.js` (THIS is where BrowserView works)

```js
const { app, BrowserWindow, BrowserView } = require('electron');

let mainWindow;
let view;

app.whenReady().then(() => {
  mainWindow = new BrowserWindow({
    width: 1200,
    height: 800,
  });

  // Create BrowserView (real browser)
  view = new BrowserView({
    webPreferences: {
      nodeIntegration: false,
      contextIsolation: true,
    },
  });

  mainWindow.setBrowserView(view);

  // Size + position
  view.setBounds({ x: 0, y: 0, width: 1200, height: 800 });
  view.setAutoResize({ width: true, height: true });

  // Load real website
  view.webContents.loadURL('https://www.google.com');

  // Optional: open devtools
  view.webContents.openDevTools();
});
```

---

## ▶️ Run it

```bash
npx electron .
```

👉 You now have:

* A **real Chromium browser**
* No iframe restrictions
* Full DevTools
* Works with Google, YouTube, etc.

