# 🔥 3. Add BrowserView in main process

Open:

```text
src/vs/code/electron-main/app.ts
```

or

```text
src/vs/code/electron-main/window.ts
```

---

## Inject BrowserView

Find where the main window is created:

```ts
const win = new BrowserWindow(...)
```

Now add:

```ts
import { BrowserView } from 'electron';

let browserView: BrowserView | null = null;

function createBrowserView(win: BrowserWindow, url: string) {
  browserView = new BrowserView({
    webPreferences: {
      nodeIntegration: false,
      contextIsolation: true,
    },
  });

  win.setBrowserView(browserView);

  browserView.setBounds({
    x: 0,
    y: 80, // leave space for VS Code title bar
    width: 1200,
    height: 800,
  });

  browserView.setAutoResize({ width: true, height: true });

  browserView.webContents.loadURL(url);
}
```

---

# 🧠 4. Trigger it from the UI (critical bridge)

Now you need:

```text
Workbench (renderer)
   → send IPC
Main process
   → create BrowserView
```

---

## 📡 Add IPC handler (main process)

```ts
import { ipcMain } from 'electron';

ipcMain.handle('open-browser', (event, url: string) => {
  const win = BrowserWindow.fromWebContents(event.sender);
  if (win) {
    createBrowserView(win, url);
  }
});
```

---

## 🖥️ Call it from workbench

Go to something like:

```text
src/vs/workbench/browser/actions/
```

Create a new action:

```ts
import { ipcRenderer } from 'electron';

ipcRenderer.invoke('open-browser', 'https://google.com');
```

👉 Now clicking your action opens a **real browser inside VS Code window**.

